        5
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D) Trisodium citrate </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">Option D:</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\"><strong>Trisodium citrate </strong>is the <strong>correct anticoagulant</strong> commonly used in<strong> coagulation studies</strong>. It <strong>chelates calcium ions</strong>, <strong>preventing blood</strong> <strong>clotting </strong>during tests such as<strong> prothrombin time (PT) and activated partial thromboplastin time (APTT). </strong>The standard concentration of<strong> trisodium citrate used for coagulation studies </strong>is typically<strong> 3.2%.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Trisodium citrate </strong>is the<strong> correct </strong>anticoagulant for<strong> coagulation studies. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">It chelates calcium ions and is used to prevent blood clotting during tests like prothrombin time (PT) and activated partial thromboplastin time (APTT). </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The standard concentration of trisodium citrate used for coagulation studies is 3.2%.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">Option A.</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\"> <strong>Calcium citrate</strong> is <strong>not</strong> commonly used as an a<strong>nticoagulant in coagulation studies</strong>. In fact, it contains <strong>calcium ions</strong>, which <strong>promote clotting rather than preventing it</strong>. Therefore, it is <strong>not suitable </strong>for use in <strong>coagulation tests.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">Option B.</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\"> <strong>EDTA </strong>is commonly used as an<strong> anticoagulant </strong>for blood samples for tests<strong> </strong>such as<strong> complete blood count (CBC). </strong>However, it is <strong>not </strong>typically used in <strong>coagulation studies </strong>because it can <strong>interfere with calcium-dependent coagulation pathways.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">Option C.</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\"> <strong>Sodium bromide</strong> is <strong>not </strong>commonly used as an <strong>anticoagulant in coagulation studies</strong>. It is primarily used in <strong>analytical chemistry </strong>and <strong>not for blood sample collection </strong>or <strong>coagulation tests</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/04/10/picture5.jpg\" style=\"height:343px; width:400px\" /></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">Educational objective: </span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Trisodium citrate is the correct anticoagulant for coagulation studies. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">It <strong>chelates calcium ions </strong>and is used to prevent <strong>blood clotting </strong>during tests like <strong>prothrombin time (PT) and activated partial thromboplastin time (APTT). </strong></span></span></span></p>",
