      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D) All of the above </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">All the three options; <strong>EDTA (Ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid), oxalate, and sodium citrate are anticoagulants that chelate calcium. </strong>They prevent <strong>blood clotting by binding to calcium ions</strong>, which are essential for th<strong>e coagulation cascade</strong>. Each of these anticoagulants is used for <strong>specific purposes </strong>in laboratory settings, depending on the<strong> type of testing required.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Book Antiqua&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"color:black\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">Option A.</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\"><strong> EDTA </strong>is an<strong> anticoagulant</strong> commonly used in laboratory settings for tests such as<strong> complete blood count (CBC)</strong>. It <strong>chelates calcium ions</strong>,<strong> preventing blood clotting by binding to calcium</strong>, which is essential for the coagulation cascade.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">Option B.</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\"><strong>&nbsp;Oxalate </strong>is <strong>another anticoagulant </strong>that chelates <strong>calcium ions</strong>, thus preventing <strong>blood clotting</strong>. It is commonly used in laboratory settings for tests such as<strong> blood glucose measurement</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">Option C.</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\"> <strong>Sodium citrate </strong>is a <strong>third anticoagulant </strong>that chelates<strong> calcium ions</strong>, effectively <strong>preventing blood clotting </strong>during various laboratory tests. It is commonly used for coagulation studies such as<strong> prothrombin time (PT) and activated partial thromboplastin time (APTT).</strong></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\">Educational objective: </span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><span style=\"color:#0d0d0d\"><strong>EDTA, oxalate, and sodium citrate </strong>are all<strong> anticoagulants </strong>commonly used in laboratory settings. They prevent <strong>blood clotting by chelating calcium ions</strong>, which are essential for the <strong>coagulation cascade</strong>. Each anticoagulant has its <strong>specific applications in different types of laboratory tests</strong>.</span></span></span></p>",
